	<h3>Figurative</h3>
	<p>If Pope&rsquo;s phrase &ldquo;ranged in order&rdquo; had been written in Arabic he might have used the verb <em>jannasa</em>, &ldquo;to make things similar&rdquo; and also &ldquo;to sort or classify.&rdquo; It has a noun form, <em>jins</em>, a genre or class, but also gender, race or nation, also a state of being. In Persian you may call someone <em>bad-jens</em>. (<em>Bad </em>in Persian means English &ldquo;bad,&rdquo; pronounced the same way.) It means they&rsquo;re mischievous, perhaps malicious, difficult, though I should add that I have heard it used with ironic affection between friends more often than I&rsquo;ve heard it as an actual insult. (Insults attract irony.) In an abstract form, <em>jensiyyat</em>, you find it on the card you fill out at the end of a flight, as your airplane is beginning to descend. The category after <em>ism</em>, &ldquo;name,&rdquo; is <em>jensiyyat</em>, &ldquo;sex,&rdquo; ( <em>al-jins</em> in Arabic, <em>cinsiyet</em> in Turkish), the one with an M and an F to choose between.</p>
	<p><em>Maj&acirc;z</em> in Arabic, and in Persian, means a crossing or a passage, but also metaphor, or figurative speech in general. Omar Khayyam, who characteristically strives for realism, likes to argue for the tangible and skeptical.</p>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p>&#1575;&#1740; &#1583;&#1604; &#1670;&#1608; &#1581;&#1602;&#1740;&#1602;&#1578; &#1580;&#1607;&#1575;&#1606; &#1607;&#1587;&#1578; &#1605;&#1580;&#1575;&#1586;<br>
	&#1670;&#1606;&#1583;&#1740;&#1606; &#1670;&#1607; &#1576;&#1585;&#1740; &#1582;&#1608;&#1575;&#1585;&#1740; &#1575;&#1586; &#1575;&#1740;&#1606; &#1585;&#1606;&#1580; &#1608; &#1606;&#1740;&#1575;&#1586;</p>
	
	<p><em>Ay del chu &#7717;aq&icirc;qat-e jah&acirc;n hast maj&acirc;z</br>
	Chand&icirc;n che kh&acirc;r&icirc; az-&icirc;n ranj-o niy&acirc;z . . .</em> .</p>
	
	<p>[Oh heart (<em>del</em>), since the truth of this world (<em>jah&acirc;n</em>) is nothing but <em>maj&acirc;z</em><br>
	Why be so upset about all this pain? . . .]</p>
	</blockquote>
	
	<p><em>Maj&acirc;z</em>, from the Arabic Jim stem J-W-Z (<em>j&acirc;za</em>, to pass through, travel &ndash; no relation to <em>jens</em>), is another Jim word used in Persian and Turkish for figurative language. <em>Maj&acirc;z</em> can have a bad reputation, as rhetoric has in English. (&ldquo;That&rsquo;s just rhetoric&rdquo; we say.) Ordinarily we think of <em>maj&acirc;z</em> as a phenomenon opposed to Jim word <em>jah&acirc;n</em>, the world, <em>jah&acirc;n</em> being a term for concrete reality rather than imagination. And since we usually consider Khayy&acirc;m a spokesman for the physical world, we don&rsquo;t expect him to say that concrete reality is identical to <em>maj&acirc;z</em> &mdash; i.e. that the physical world is a metaphor, an illusion. An Iranian friend who many years ago was teaching me this poem observed that it was <em>jabri</em>, fatalistic. I suppose a <em>jav&acirc;b</em> might be that <em>maj&acirc;z</em> also has a religious meaning. It could mean an allegory like <em>Pilgrim&rsquo;s Progress</em>, where the concrete world, the one we see, is just a language. From the point of view of the right believer, you could read it and find the meaning of things. E.G. Browne in his <em>Literary History of Persia </em>cites an Arabic proverb: &ldquo;<em>Al-Maj&acirc;zu qanṭar-u&rsquo;l-&#7716;aq&icirc;qa</em>.&rdquo; &ldquo;The figurative is the bridge to the Truth&rdquo; (i.442). We know already that even the alphabet can be taken as a mystical key to reality. (The discipline is called <em>jafr</em>.) More than likely this is not the best way to read the poem.</p>
	
