	<h3>Literal</h3>
	<p>The shapes of letters, static shapes of ink on a page, are not figurative. They&rsquo;re really there. A poem referring to its own letters is literal (in both senses). Persian poetry likes to combine the traditional theme of watching a love object, transfixed by beauty, with the evocation of a beauty spot. That dark circle can be the occasion for a <em>maj&acirc;z</em> which circles something literal. A <em>kh&acirc;l</em>, a beauty spot, is a sign of beauty. It is also easy to compare to the dot in a letter.</p>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p>&#1583;&#1585; &#1582;&#1605; &#1586;&#1604;&#1601; &#1578;&#1608; &#1570;&#1606; &#1582;&#1575;&#1604; &#1587;&#1740;&#1575;&#1607; &#1583;&#1575;&#1606;&#1740; &#1670;&#1740;&#1587;&#1578;</br>
	<p>&#1606;&#1602;&#1578;&#1607; &#1740; &#1583;&#1608;&#1583;&#1607; &#1705;&#1607; &#1583;&#1585; &#1581;&#1604;&#1602;&#1607; &#1740; &#1580;&#1740;&#1605; &#1575;&#1601;&#1578;&#1575;&#1583; &#1575;&#1587;&#1578;</p>
	
	<p><em>Dar kham-e zolf-e tow &acirc;n kh&acirc;l-e siyah d&acirc;n&icirc; chist:<br>
	Noq&#7789;eh-ye dudeh ke dar &#7717;alqeh-ye J&icirc;m aft&acirc;d ast.</em></p>
	
	<p>[The beauty spot seen in the falling curve of your hair: you know already what it is. it&rsquo;s that dark dot in the curve of Jim.]</p>
	</blockquote>
	
	
	<p>We translate <em>kh&acirc;l</em> variously (spot, mole, beauty spot), but none of them sound quite right. For that matter it&rsquo;s hard to translate <em>dudeh</em>, the color of the <em>kh&acirc;l</em>. It&rsquo;s easier to translate its color: <em>Dud</em> is smoke (like the smoke from Khorasan in <a href="http://alifbatourguide.com/the-arabic-alphabet/ta/">Chapter Ta</a>); <em>dudeh</em> is soot. A <em>noqṭeh-ye dudeh</em> is a sooty/black dot.</p>
	<p>Jim at the end of the couplet (<em>J&icirc;m aft&acirc;d ast</em>) is, again, literal, in the sense that it is the physical letter, made of sooty ink, but it is also figurative, since the loop of the terminal Jim becomes her hair and her <em>kh&acirc;l </em>the dot framed by it. A fluid translation by Jila Peacock (a great contemporary calligrapher), catches all of it:</p>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p>The dusky mole encircled by your curls,<br>
	Is like the ink-drop falling in the curve of J.<br>
	(Jila Peacock, 24)</p>
	</blockquote>
	
	<p>(There is <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PUhaF1JI5r8">an extraordinary video</a> based on her calligraphy, which shows the dot drifting into the curve of a stand-alone Jim.)</p>
	
	<h3>Logo of the Arab World</h3>
	<p>Jim is for <em>jam&icirc;l</em>, &ldquo;beautiful,&rdquo; &ldquo;stately,&rdquo; &ldquo;dignified.&rdquo; Of the two most commonly heard Arabic words for beautiful, <em>jam&icirc;l</em> and <em>&#7716;alw</em>, <em>jam&icirc;l</em> is the elevated one. In the narrative of Joseph, as told in Sura Twelve of the Qur&rsquo;&acirc;n, when his father is first told of Joseph&rsquo;s mysterious absence, his response is &ldquo;<em>ṣabrun jam&icirc;lun</em>,&rdquo; &ldquo;Patience is beautiful&rdquo; (12.18), thus establishing that beauty has an ethical overtone. In a noun form, <em>jam&acirc;l</em>, from the same stem, means glory or splendor, as in the name Jam&acirc;l al-Din, &ldquo;Splendor of the religion,&rdquo; or in a charming passage from the sixteenth sura of the Qur&rsquo;&acirc;n, where praise of creation turns to the example of cattle. They have elegance, beauty: &ldquo;<em>wa lakum f&icirc;-h&acirc; jam&acirc;lun</em> <em>h&icirc;na tur&icirc;h&ucirc;na wa h&icirc;na tasrah&ucirc;na</em>&rdquo; (You have [in the cattle] <em>jam&acirc;l</em> when you lead them home in the evening or out in the morning -- Q 16.6) Linking cattle with <em>jam&acirc;l </em>takes some ingenuity in English. Penrice&rsquo;s dictionary of the Qur&rsquo;an suggests &ldquo;they are a credit to you,&rdquo; definitely a let-down. A.J. Arberry makes it more personal: &ldquo;and there is beauty in them for you.&rdquo; Yusuf Ali says &ldquo;and you feel a sense of pride and beauty in them .&rdquo; Yusuf Ali comes closest to seeing in <em>jam&acirc;l</em> that hyperbolic magnificence present even in the ambling of one&rsquo;s own domestic animals.</p>
	<p>I almost don&rsquo;t want to bring up the best known cognate of the word <em>jam&icirc;l</em>. The stem, J&ndash;M&ndash;L, <em>jamala</em>, means &ldquo;to collect, assemble.&rdquo; The simplest noun form is <em>jamal</em>, source of English &ldquo;camel,&rdquo; an innocent animal whose image has become, seen from abroad, the official mascot of the Middle East. The logo of Camel cigarettes, perhaps the most famous of our Camel icons, stems from the claim that the tobacco was from Turkey, probably meaning by synecdoche the Middle East in general. The picture shows palm trees and pyramids in the background, so it certainly isn&rsquo;t Turkey in any literal way.</p>
	<p>It is generally understood that if you sum up an entire culture of the global population by an animal, there&rsquo;s something demeaning in it. (Football teams have animal mascots, and no one seems to mind, but a culture isn&rsquo;t a football team.) A logo can infantilize a culture, but then again camels were indeed important to the desert economy, for all the reasons the textbooks will tell you. A cigar, as Freud is believed to have said, is sometimes just a cigar. A camel is sometimes just a camel. From Egypt to Iran, in any of the Middle Eastern communities with a desert ecology, you really do run into them. You meet camels in classical Arabic poetry. A camel is down there underlying the alphabet. As Alif grows from a stylized ox and Ba from a stylized house, Jim (like Gimel in Hebrew) grows from a stylized camel.</p>
	
