	<h3>Ironic</h3>
	<p>If we judged from the catalogues of <em>maj&acirc;z</em>, we would conclude that irony barely exists in Middle Eastern rhetoric. In Europe we like to claim irony as our own possession, the trope we trace back to Plato. (Plato was called an <em>eiron</em>.) It is a shame that in Arabic there is no more focused, precise word for it. The thing certainly exists. (The terms for &ldquo;irony&rdquo; in Arabic stake out slightly different territory: <em>tahakkum</em>, mockery, derision; <em>sukhr&icirc;ya</em>, scorn, mockery; or <em>ta&lsquo;nah</em>, attack, calumny, vilification.) I&rsquo;d prefer a definition which conveys that irony is simply a shift of voice, or point of view, playing dumb, a pretense of agreeing with an opponent when in fact we don&rsquo;t. That would be nice. But in fact, without the name, mock agreement, or irony, is one of the most widespread and powerful of devices throughout the Middle East. There is a story in the <em>Thousand and One Nights</em> (the story of the Barber&rsquo;s sixth brother) in which an impoverished protagonist stumbles into the mansion of the (historical) Barmaki family, wealthy dignitaries in the early Abbasid court. The host invites him in as the only guest at an imaginary banquet, offering a non-existent ewer to wash his hands with and a series of imagined extravagant dishes, a dinner which obviously torments the hungry guest. The menu includes an imaginary serving of wine. The visitor plays along with the game and joins the pantomime, pretending he enjoys the dinner and that the wine has made him drunk. The story becomes funny at the moment he slaps his host, arguing that he has to be forgiven. Look how drunk he was. The host appreciates his irony and the episode ends happily. The story even has its influence outside the Arab world; the phrase &ldquo;Barmecide Feast&rdquo; (Barmecide meaning Barmaki) is still in English dictionaries.</p>
	<p>There is a camel in the story collection, <em>Kal&icirc;la wa Dimna</em>, who experiences irony but never gets to appreciate it. The story-teller is the ox Shatraba, who tells it as part of a gloomy debate with the villainous jackal Dimna. Dimna, determined to create discord, wants the ox to battle the lion. Shatraba knows it is a bad idea no matter who wins. He is after all the lion&rsquo;s friend. And yet he also knows Dimna has made the lion suspicious of him, and the fight is inevitable. He tells the camel&rsquo;s story not to argue his case, but to explain that he sees through Dimna&rsquo;s plans. The camel in the story is, like Shatraba, a refugee from human domestication who, like him, wanders into the world of animals in the wild. He joins a kind of miniature society in a paradisical community: a thicket of trees [<em>ajama</em>] neighboring a road [<em>muj&acirc;waratin tar&icirc;qan</em>] apart from among the roads of men, like the court where <em>Kalila and Dimna</em>&rsquo;s frame story takes place.</p>
	<p>In Shatraba&rsquo;s account the <em>jamal</em> finds some friends &mdash; a raven, a wolf and a jackal. They form a kind of commune with a lion for their protector, just like the community in which the ox and the jackals live. Raven, wolf and jackal live amicably with their new immigrant camel friend until the lion is wounded in combat with an elephant, and can no longer provide them with food. Spurred on by <em>ju&lsquo;</em>, hunger, they start to look at the <em>jamal </em>with renewed interest as a source of meat and they start to conspire. The <em>jamal</em> has the vulnerability of a new citizen, but he is nonetheless protected by the lion with an oath of loyalty. The raven, wolf and jackal decide to kill him and share the camel meat, but to stay within the terms of the oath. The stratagem requires a series of self-sacrificing, persuasive, ironic speeches in which one by one raven, jackal and wolf offer themselves as a meal. Each time by pre-arrangement the offer is politely declined. The first to make his offer (here in A. J. Arberry&rsquo;s translation) is the raven:</p>


	<blockquote>
	<p>. . . &ldquo;Now the king is in need, though my body and soul are but poor, weak things, I offer them joyfully to ransom the king&rsquo;s royal person. The king may be able to assuage his pangs for today by eating my flesh; so let him slay me.&rdquo;</p>
	<p>&ldquo;Why, what good would come of eating you?&rdquo; the others objected. &ldquo;Your skin and bones would make a very poor meal.&rdquo;</p>
	<p>The jackal next started off in the same fashion.</p>
	<p>&ldquo;No, no,&rdquo; the others shouted. &ldquo;Your flesh stinks and is bad to eat. It&rsquo;s not at all suitable for the king&rsquo;s dinner.&rdquo;</p>
	<p>The wolf followed suit . . . (Arberry, 106-07)</p>
	</blockquote>
	
	<p>We are in a second level of irony here: the camel in Shatraba&rsquo;s story believes he has read his audience correctly and mastered the rules of their discourse, but in fact he&rsquo;s descending into a trap. There is another set of rules at work, so when the camel follows suit, offering his body as a sacrifice, this time they surprise him by accepting, and quickly. (&ldquo;You&rsquo;re right, you&rsquo;re right,&rdquo; they exclaimed with one voice . . . And they fell upon him and tore him to pieces.&rdquo;) They have, in other words, entered his discourse, pretending to take him literally. Ironically.</p>
	
	<h3>G</h3>
	<p>J sounds in Arabic often have cognates in neighboring Semitic languages with a hard G sound, Hebrew supplying examples, such as the angel Gabriel who in Arabic is Jabra&rsquo;&icirc;l or Jibril. For some reason the Egyptian dialect also uses the hard G when pronouncing words with Jim, and it is a hard habit to shake. This is why, in specialist writing, you will see the name Naguib Mahfouz spelled Naj&icirc;b Mahf&ucirc;z, with our J. Non-Egyptian Arabs who see the name Naj&icirc;b pronounce it in the soft form, as a J. Egyptians see the same letter and are likely to hear it as a G. (The U in &ldquo;Naguib&rdquo; is the French stratagem used on some occasions to represent a hard G, as in <em>gu&eacute;rilla</em>, <em>guillotine</em> or <em>guitar</em>.) The first name, Jam&acirc;l, of the charismatic Egyptian ruler &lsquo;Abd al-N&acirc;sir, becomes in our newspapers and reference works Gamal, perhaps because journalists who transcribed it in the fifties when he rose to power simply wrote it down as informants pronounced it, as Gamal Abdul-Nasser.</p>
	<p>The most famous coffee house in Cairo used to be Groppi&rsquo;s, founded in 1909 by Giacomo Groppi (1863-1947), an entrepreneur from Lugano. The elegant calligraphy over the doorway (shown in neon on their FaceBook page) begins with a Jim. (The P sound, by the way, is rendered Persian style, a Ba with three dots.) Western visitors to Cairo are likely to have seen the place name Gezira, a suburb located on an island in the Nile. Al-Jaz&icirc;ra, with a J sound, is the word for island. The stem, J-Z-R, means to slaughter, butcher, probably because an island is cut off from the mainland. (After Napoleon&rsquo;s incursion into Egypt in 1798 it was Ahmad Pasha, called al-Jazz&acirc;r, The Butcher, whose armies finally pushed the French out.) In its plural form <em>jaz&icirc;ra </em>becomes <em>jaz&acirc;&rsquo;ir</em>, which gives us Al-jaz&acirc;&rsquo;ir, for some reason the Arabic name of Algeria. Qatar is strictly speaking a peninsula rather than an island, but the news service called Al Jazeera (<em>Al-Jaz&icirc;ra</em>) was developed there; westerners can identify the newspaper&rsquo;s distinctive logo, though they may not notice a hidden Jim at its kernel. It has a history: <a href="https://carsonparkdesign.com/al-jazeera-logo/">the logo</a> was created by a non-professional Qatari calligrapher who competed with established design companies in a nation-wide contest. The Jim is next to the right border, but it&rsquo;s not easy to spot without a coach. </p>
	
	<h3>A Word We Won&rsquo;t Get Back</h3>
	<p>We&rsquo;ve come to feel at home with the name Al-Jazeera. Just another foreign name, like <em>Der Spiegel</em> or <em>Le Monde</em>. By comparison the Arabic word &ldquo;jihad&rdquo; has pretty much become an English word. It has been granted passage into daily speech, but not without a price. Western observers always seem to believe that they know what it means.</p>
	<p>There is a song called &ldquo;Jihad&rdquo; by the band Slayer (from the album <em>Christ Illusion</em>, 2006). It doesn&rsquo;t imitate Middle Eastern music in any way, but the violence of its imagery is meant to sound like an imagined terrorist, opponent of the west. (&ldquo;I well see you burned alive screaming for your God / I will hunt you down again for Him.&rdquo;). It&rsquo;s a stylized poem, patched together out of the mandatory violent images of the genre. They sing it with rage. It&rsquo;s irony, though the direction of that irony is hard to read. It seems to say &ldquo;I hate this guy, but I&rsquo;m still going to steal his voice.&rdquo; We could add &ldquo;that&rsquo;s funny &mdash; his voice sounds like mine.&rdquo; It is said that American troops in Iraq went into fire-fights playing that song. Is it parody? (This is what you sound like to me.) Just imitation? (Look, I can sound just like you.) Or homage?</p>
	<p>It ought to be possible to explain that J-H-D is simply the stem &ldquo;to endeavor,&rdquo; &ldquo;to strive.&rdquo; &ldquo;Jihad,&rdquo; says Reza Aslan, &ldquo;implies a struggle against the self, against one&rsquo;s passions and instincts and the temptations that oppress the soul&rdquo; (xvii). It occurs in the Qur&rsquo;an in both senses &mdash; the internal vision in &ldquo;<em>Kharajtum jih&acirc;dan fi sab&icirc;l&icirc; </em>&rdquo; (in Yusuf Ali&rsquo;s version, &ldquo;If ye have come out to strive in my way . . .&rdquo; &ndash; Q 60.1). You can find more complex meanings, as in Q 25.52 &mdash; &ldquo;Therefore listen not to the unbelievers, but strive against them with the utmost strenuousness.&rdquo; The inner meaning is the kernel, but in English it has come to mean holy war in the belligerent sense. (Even in the otherwise sensible <em>American Heritage Dictionary</em>.) Once a word has undergone this kind of metamorphosis, as we know from more than one example, the degraded form tends to stick. English speakers aren&rsquo;t getting the original meaning back any time soon.</p>
	<p>The interested should know that the term <em>jih&acirc;d</em> also occurs in the Arabic New Testament: the phrase from Colossians (chapter 2, verse 1) which the 1611 English Bible translates &ldquo;For I would that ye knew what great conflict I had for you&rdquo; (Colossians 2.1). &ldquo;Conflict&rdquo; translates the Greek <em>agon</em>, &ldquo;struggle, contest, battle.&rdquo; In an Arabic version the word is <em>jih&acirc;d</em>.</p>
	
